SIMPLE: patter
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patter
<hw>Pat"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pattered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Pattering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>pat</ets> to strike gently.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To strike with
a quick succession of slight, sharp sounds; <as>as, <ex>pattering</ex>
rain or hail; <ex>pattering</ex> feet.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stealing shower is scarce to <qex>patter</qex> heard.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mutter; to mumble; <as>as, to <ex>patter</ex>
with the lips</as>.</def> <au>Tyndale.</au> <ety>[In this sense, and in
the following, perh. from <ets>pater</ets>noster.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To talk glibly; to chatter; to harangue.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I've gone out and <qex>pattered</qex> to get money.</q>
<rj><qau>Mayhew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Patter
<hw>Pat"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To spatter; to
sprinkle.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧And <xex>patter</xex> the water
about the boat.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>J. R. Drake.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Patter</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, 2.]</ety>
<def>To mutter; as prayers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The hooded clouds] <qex>patter</qex> their doleful prayers.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To patter flash</b></col>, <cd>to talk in thieves'
cant.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Patter
<hw>Pat"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A quick succession of
slight sounds; <as>as, the <ex>patter</ex> of rain; the <ex>patter</ex>
of little feet.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Glib and rapid speech; a voluble harangue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The cant of a class; patois; <as>as, thieves's
<ex>patter</ex>; gypsies' <ex>patter</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The language or oratory of a street peddler,
conjurer, or the like, hence, glib talk; a voluble harangue; mere talk;
chatter; also, specif., rapid speech, esp. as sometimes introduced in
songs.</def> <mark>[Cant or Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Patterer</ent>⟦br⟧
